onship\n3. read session metadata, turns, and transcript records\n4. render records grouped by turn, or choose a recent turn window\n5. include environment snapshots only when useful for re-orientation\n\nFor review sharing:\n\n1. start from a branch, change, or PR\n2. use derived lookup indexes to find candidate turns and sessions\n3. resolve project-scoped sessions for those candidates\n4. read t\n[TRUNCATED]\nsociation work is split across write and read time:\n\n- **Capture time:** write observations and deterministic index memberships from\n  the current capture turn snapshot, such as observed branch names, review ids,\n  and change ids.\n- **Read time:** answer association questions by looking up candidate turns from\n  indexes, reading their observations, and scoring/explaining likely related\n  sessions with the current heuristic version.\n\nCapture should not write final inferred relationships such as \"this PR is\nassociated with this session\" or \"this branch was produced by this session.\"\nIt only writes the facts and lookup entries needed to answer those questions\nefficiently later.\n\nThe index is not the association. It is a disposable acceleration structure.\nIf the heuristic changes, a future namespace or rebuild can let old sessions\nbenefit retroactively.\n\nFor v1, write only branch, review, and change indexes:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agentlog-index-version = 1\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:<target-key-hash> = set<IndexHit JSON string>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:<target-key-hash> = set<IndexHit JSON string>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:change:<target-key-hash> = set<IndexHit JSON string>\n```\n\nThe index value includes both the session key and turn key so an index lookup can\nresolve directly to the owning session without scanning session turn lists. Use\na compact JSON string value rather than a custom delimiter:\n\n```json\n{\"session_key\":\"sha256-...\",\"turn_key\":\"sha256-...\"}\n```\n\nIndex key material may contain slashes, remote URLs, provider ids, or arbitrary\nchange-id bytes. Hash target key material for GitMeta key names and keep the\nreadable canonical values in `observed_targets`.\n\nDo not write a path index in v1. Path-level keys can explode with large commits,\nbroad worktree changes, generated files, or dependency lockfile churn. File\npaths remain in the turn observations for scoring after branch/review/change\ncandidate discovery.\n\nIndex entries are candidate discovery only. Readers must verify candidates by\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T13:49:58.888Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}